{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17539619","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17539619"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:44:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16684"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16684","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16684"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.22,0.12,0.1,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66344"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9375"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16684"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51794"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1713"},{"type":"tags","id":"2333"},{"type":"tags","id":"4072"},{"type":"tags","id":"4074"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22188"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43638"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66344","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66344"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the obstetrician for her six-week postnatal check. She has had an uncomplicated vaginal delivery of her first child and is mixed feeding, supplementing four to five breastfeeds daily with formula. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She asks about the reliability of breastfeeding as a method of contraception as she and her partner wish to avoid pregnancy for at least two years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. She has not had any vaginal bleeding since her lochia resolved three weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the effectiveness of lactational amenorrhea as contraception in this patient?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Less than 10% effective due to mixed feeding","60% effective while amenorrhoeic","98% effective for six months","75% effective until menses returns","90% effective while any breastfeeding continues"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is using mixed feeding, which significantly reduces the effectiveness of lactational amenorrhea as a contraceptive method. The Lactational Amenorrhea Method (LAM) requires three strict criteria: exclusive breastfeeding with no supplemental feeds, amenorrhea (no menstrual bleeding after 56 days postpartum), and infant less than six months old.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELess than 10% effective due to mixed feeding\u003C/strong\u003E reflects the significantly reduced contraceptive effect when supplemental feeds are introduced. The introduction of formula disrupts the intensive suckling pattern required to maintain lactational amenorrhea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E60% effective while amenorrhoeic\u003C/strong\u003E overstates the effectiveness in this scenario. While amenorrhea is one criterion for LAM, the introduction of formula feeding has already compromised its reliability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E98% effective for six months\u003C/strong\u003E would only be true if all three LAM criteria were met, which is not the case here due to mixed feeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E75% effective until menses returns\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as ovulation can occur before the first menstrual period, and the mixed feeding pattern has already compromised the method\u0027s effectiveness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E90% effective while any breastfeeding continues\u003C/strong\u003E significantly overstates the effectiveness. The contraceptive effect requires exclusive breastfeeding, not partial breastfeeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhen counselling about contraception, it is important to emphasise that alternative methods should be used when any of the LAM criteria are not met. In this case, the patient requires immediate alternative contraception as she is mixed feeding.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactational amenorrhea is over 98% effective as contraception when all three LAM criteria are met: exclusive breastfeeding, amenorrhea, and less than 6 months postpartum.","Mixed feeding significantly reduces the contraceptive effectiveness of lactational amenorrhea.","Alternative contraception should be recommended when any LAM criteria are not met."],"references":["Family Planning NSW. Fertility Awareness-Based Methods of Contraception and the Lactational Amenorrhoea Method [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://www.fpnsw.org.au/health-information/contraception/fertility-awareness-based-methods-contraception-lactational","Australian Breastfeeding Association. Getting pregnant while breastfeeding [Internet]. [cited 2024 Nov 29]. Available from: https://www.breastfeeding.asn.au/resources/getting-pregnant-while-breastfeeding#:~:text=Studies%20have%20shown%20that%20LAM,no%20other%20foods%20or%20drinks)."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51794"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16684"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51794","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51794"},"attributes":{"cr